tIndex of languages -- tGeneral index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume presents the Egyptian-Coptic language in cross-linguistic (‘typological’) perspective. It is aimed at linguists of all stripes, especially typologists, historical linguists, and specialists in Egyptian-Coptic, Afroasiatic languages, or African languages. Uniquely, the contributions are written by both typologists and experts of Egyptian-Coptic and typologists. The former provide case studies dealing with particular aspects of the various phases of the Egyptian-Coptic language (e.g., COLLIER on conditional constructions), while the latter situate Egyptian-Coptic data in cross-linguistic perspective (e.g., those by GUELDEMANN and GENSLER). The volume also includes an introductory section that includes an overview of the Egyptian-Coptic language (HASPELMATH), a sketch of its sociohistorical setting (GROSSMAN & RICHTER), its relationship with language typology (RICHTER), and the way in which Egyptian-Coptic data should be presented to nonspecialists, focusing on transliteration and glossing (GROSSMAN & HASPELMATH).This is the first book to bring together language typology and the Egyptian-Coptic language in an explicit fashion.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCoptic languagexGrammar, Comparative. 0aEgyptian languagexGrammar, Comparative. 0aTypology (Linguistics) 0aTypology (Linguistics). 4aSprachtypologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican Languages.  aAfroasiatic Languages.  aEgyptian-Coptic.1 aCollier, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGensler, Orin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrossman, Eitan, econ